\begin_layout Abstract
A growing consensus holds that the theory of land rent has deteriorated
 and needs restoration.
 This paper contributes to this project by fundamentally rethinking land
 rent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The first, empirical part analyzes aggregate land values in the U.S.
 and demonstrates that land rent was the source of the housing bubble that
 triggered the crisis of the early 21st century.
 Yet almost all heterodox writing on the crisis, including that by economic
 geographers, ignores land rent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The second part seeks reasons for this in land rent's history.
 During the 1970s, geographers grew critical of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spatial science
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 paradigm and turned to geographical political economy, drawing primarily
 from Marx.
 Since the dominant theory of urban form relied on the neoclassical theory
 of land rent, geographers looked to Marx for a substitute.
 But Marx planned to devote an entire volume of 
\emph on
Capital
\emph default
 to land rent and died before he could write it.
 I argue that this fully elaborated Marxist theory of land rent would be
 closer to Quesnay's 
\emph on
\lang french
Tableau Ã©conomique
\emph default
\lang american
 than Alonso's bid rent curves, and the quest for a theory of urban form
 based on rent-extraction mechanisms discussed in Volume 3 of 
\emph on
Capital
\emph default
 sidetracked economic geography.
 Additionally, during the 1990s economic geography's increasing fragmentation
 accelerated land-rent theory's decline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Part three proposes a way forward.
 It examines the ontology of land rent and debunks the common belief that
 land rent arises because the supply of land is fixed.
 Instead, land rent arises from the time required to alter land supply.
 Land can be produced and enters into the production of other commodities
 and final consumption.
 The paper outlines a macroeconomic land-rent theory combining Marxian political
 economy, Austro-Georgist theories of real-estate cycles, and Post-Keynesian/Min
skyan theories of asset-price speculation and financial instability.
\end_layout

